CIC/References/HTTP2_Message_Format.html.body:
HTTP/2 message
All communications with CIC is done over the HTTP/2 protocol. This picture shows how an HTTP/2 message is structured when your client sends a message to CIC.

The following topics are covered in this section.

HTTP request
CIC base URL
HTTP header
HTTP multipart message


HTTP response

HTTP request 
Typically, an HTTP request is sent when your client delivers a user request to CIC using an Event message.
CIC base URL 
Clova uses the following URL as a base URL.
https://prod-ni-cic.clova.ai/
HTTP header 
The following header is required when connecting to CIC.
:method = {{GET|POST}}
:scheme = https
:path = /{{API Version}}/{{events|directives}}
Authorization = Bearer {{Clova access token}}
content-type = multipart/form-data; boundary={{boundary_term}}



Field name
Message description




:method
CIC supports the following methods. GET: Used when creating a DownchannelPOST: Used when sending an Event message


:scheme
The CIC APIs support HTTPS communication.


:path
Event and Directive messages use the following paths. /v1/events/v1/directives


authorization
Enter an authorization token obtained from the Clova authorization server. An authorization token should be included in the header of all requests.


content-type
The content type of the HTTP message. Use multipart/form-data because it is a multipart message. Also, specify a message boundary term to separate messages and make the term invisible in the message body. The content type of each message is defined in its message header.



HTTP multipart message 
Once an HTTP header is transferred and a connection is established, a stream is created. Both CIC and your client send Event or Directive messages through this stream. Each message may carry JSON data containing information of a request or a response, or it may contain binary audio data recorded from user's speech input. Each message is structured as follows depending on the data type.
Message structure of JSON data
You use a JSON-format message when you want to send a message containing information about an Event message or content. When a message contains JSON data, the message consists of a header and a body as follows.
[ Message Header ]
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="metadata"
Content-Type: application/json; charset=UTF-8

[ Message Body ]
{
  "context": [
  ],
  "event": {
    "header": {
      "namespace": {{string}},
      "name": {{string}},
      "dialogRequestId": {{string}},
      "messageId": {{string}}
    },
    "payload": {{object}}
  }
}
Each Event message may have different components depending on the CIC API. See CIC message format and CIC API for more details on the message structure and API.
Message structure of audio data
Audio data has a header as below and contains binary data in the body. See SpeechRecognizer.Recognize for more details.
[ Message Header ]
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="audio"
Content-Type: application/octet-stream

[ PCM Audio Attachment ]
{{ Binary audio attachment }}
HTTP response 
Typically, an HTTP response is a Directive message sent from CIC. It may send the following messages in combination.

Synthesizer.Speak is a Directive message that produces audio output. It delivers audio data additionally.
AudioPlayer.Play is a Directive message that requires additional information. The message should contain JSON data such as playback streaming information.


  Note!
  Currently, we are relying on HTTP status code to provide error information but we are preparing to provide responses for exception handling soon.


HTTP message example 
This is an example of an HTTP request/response message sent and received between a client and CIC.
Request Example
:method = POST
:scheme = https
:path = /v1/events
authorization = Bearer {{clova-access-token}}
content-type = multipart/form-data; boundary=Boundary-Text

--Boundary-Text
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="metadata"
Content-Type: application/json; charset=UTF-8

{
  "context": [
    {
      "header": {
        "namespace": "Speaker",
        "name": "VolumeState"
      },
      "payload": {
        "volume": 25,
        "muted": false
      }
    }
  ],
  "event": {
    "header": {
      "namespace": "SpeechRecognizer",
      "name": "Recognize",
      "messageId": "277b40c3-b046-4f61-a551-783b1547e7b7",
      "dialogRequestId": "4e4080d6-c440-498a-bb73-ae86c6312806"
    },
    "payload": {
      "profile": "CLOSE_TALK"
    }
  }
}

--Boundary-Text

Content-Disposition: form-data; name="audio"
Content-Type: application/octet-stream

{{binary audio attachment}}
--Boundary-Text--
Response Example
:status = 200
content-type = multipart/related; boundary=Boundary-Text; type="application/json"

--Boundary-Text
Content-Type: application/json; charset=UTF-8

{
    "directive": {
        "header": {
            "namespace": "SpeechSynthesizer",
            "name": "Speak",
            "messageId": "277b40c3-b046-4f61-a551-783b1547e7b7",
            "dialogRequestId": "4e4080d6-c440-498a-bb73-ae86c6312806"
        },
        "payload": {
            "url": "cid:1234",
            "format": "AUDIO_MPEG"
            "token": "kr17447380422"
        }
    }
}

--Boundary-Text
Content-Type: application/octet-stream
Content-ID: 

{{binary audio attachment}}
--Boundary-Text--

CIC/References/APIs/PlaybackController.h.body:
PlaybackController
This API lets your client control audio playback and speaker output.

  Note!
  The PlaybackController was deprecated and is not supported any more. All the APIs which used to be provided by this namespace will be migrated to the AudioPlayer namespace in the future.


The PlaybackController API provides the following Event and Directive messages.



Message name
Message type
Message description




mute
Directive
Instructs your client to mute the speaker volume.


next
Directive
Instructs your client to start playback of the next audio stream in a playback queue.


pause
Directive
Instructs your client to pause playback of the current audio stream.


previous
Directive
Instructs your client to start playback the previous audio stream in a playback queue.


resume
Directive
Instructs your client to resume playback of the audio stream.


stop
Directive
Instructs your client to stop playback of the audio stream.


TurnOffRepeatMode
Directive
Instructs your client to turn off the repeat mode.


TurnOnRepeatMode
Directive
Instructs your client to turn on the repeat mode.


unmute
Directive
Instructs your client to unmute the speaker volume.


volumeDown
Directive
Instructs your client to turn down the speaker volume.


volumeUp
Directive
Instructs your client to turn up the speaker volume.



mute Directive 
Instructs your client to mute the speaker volume.
Payload field
None
Message example
{
    "directive": {
        "header": {
            "namespace": "PlaybackController",
            "name": "mute",
            "dialogRequestId": "dialog-id-here-1",
            "messageId": "b1f88d7d-bbb8-44fa-a0a2-c5a7553e6f8a"
        },
        "payload": {}
    }
}

See also

Speaker.VolumeState
SpeechRecognizer.Recognize

next Directive 
Instructs your client to start playback of the next audio stream in a playback queue.
Payload field
None
Message example
